WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.834 --> 00:00:04.434
Thompson:
Now we're on. Okay.

00:00:04.434 --> 00:00:07.367
Google APIs.

00:00:07.367 --> 00:00:10.601
Imagine trying to deploy

00:00:10.601 --> 00:00:12.701
services like these
on your own.

00:00:12.701 --> 00:00:14.601
The levels of redundancy,

00:00:14.601 --> 00:00:16.167
the years of development.

00:00:16.167 --> 00:00:17.667
I used to struggle
for the budget

00:00:17.667 --> 00:00:18.801
to get a second server,

00:00:18.801 --> 00:00:21.467
even for mission-critical
applications.

00:00:21.467 --> 00:00:22.901
But thousands--

00:00:22.901 --> 00:00:24.334
tens of thousands
of companies

00:00:24.334 --> 00:00:26.601
still operate that way.

00:00:26.601 --> 00:00:29.200
And eventually they'll become
a really huge market

00:00:29.200 --> 00:00:31.501
for transitions to the cloud.

00:00:31.501 --> 00:00:34.067
I've been given
a lot of opportunities

00:00:34.067 --> 00:00:36.834
to learn things
while working with Google.

00:00:36.834 --> 00:00:40.567
I've signed some severe
confidentiality agreements.

00:00:40.567 --> 00:00:42.133
I really can't blog anymore.

00:00:42.133 --> 00:00:44.067
Can't publish anything.

00:00:44.067 --> 00:00:46.000
Can't talk in my sleep.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:47.767
But I can share this.

00:00:47.767 --> 00:00:49.367
I know Google's passionate

00:00:49.367 --> 00:00:52.234
about performance
and reliability.

00:00:52.234 --> 00:00:53.534
If you can come up
with something

00:00:53.534 --> 00:00:55.434
that shaves ten milliseconds
off an operation,

00:00:55.434 --> 00:00:57.000
there's cheers all around.

00:00:57.000 --> 00:00:58.567
I've never seen
anything like it.

00:00:58.567 --> 00:01:00.801
So that's one of the reasons

00:01:00.801 --> 00:01:04.534
I would say I think Google's
the long-term best candidate

00:01:04.534 --> 00:01:06.067
to be the cloud,

00:01:06.067 --> 00:01:07.634
their APIs.

00:01:07.634 --> 00:01:10.334
There'll be others
in narrow niches,

00:01:10.334 --> 00:01:13.434
but Google
will be the gold standard.

00:01:13.434 --> 00:01:16.234
And learning to make good use
of the Google APIs

00:01:16.234 --> 00:01:18.334
is a competitive advantage,

00:01:18.334 --> 00:01:20.968
'cause right now, for the price
of an email address,

00:01:20.968 --> 00:01:22.534
on App Engine,

00:01:22.534 --> 00:01:25.367
we can have ten
of our own virtual servers.

00:01:25.367 --> 00:01:29.501
Each one can handle
7,400 requests per minute

00:01:29.501 --> 00:01:31.634
through a ten-gig pipeline.

00:01:31.634 --> 00:01:34.200
It's hard to compete
against that kind of--

00:01:34.200 --> 00:01:35.200
it's hard to compete

00:01:35.200 --> 00:01:37.167
with those kinds
of free resources

00:01:37.167 --> 00:01:39.100
if you didn't have them.

00:01:40.968 --> 00:01:42.634
This is a short list

00:01:42.634 --> 00:01:46.667
of what we consider to be
essential API tools.

00:01:49.167 --> 00:01:51.000
For us, the basics
are App Engine,

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:55.167
Base, Gadgets, Maps,
and Spreadsheets.

00:01:55.167 --> 00:01:59.000
If we get good with these,
we can cover a lot of ground.

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:03.667
Probably a lot of you know
these APIs better than I do.

00:02:03.667 --> 00:02:04.934
And I'm not here

00:02:04.934 --> 00:02:06.701
because I'm some kind
of expert on anything.

00:02:06.701 --> 00:02:08.167
I think the reason I'm here

00:02:08.167 --> 00:02:10.367
is 'cause I've been
in the industry so long,

00:02:10.367 --> 00:02:13.067
and I just work really hard,
and I work like crazy.

00:02:13.067 --> 00:02:15.100
So I'm probably
telling you some things--

00:02:15.100 --> 00:02:17.100
Maybe you already knew that.

00:02:17.100 --> 00:02:19.801
And hopefully,
there'll be something in here

00:02:19.801 --> 00:02:22.968
that you can take away
that'll be helpful to you.

00:02:22.968 --> 00:02:25.901
But I'll go through it.

00:02:25.901 --> 00:02:28.267
Google Base lets us put

00:02:28.267 --> 00:02:31.567
just about any kind
of content online.

00:02:31.567 --> 00:02:33.834
And, again, for the price
of an email address,

00:02:33.834 --> 00:02:36.934
we can put
1 million records online.

00:02:36.934 --> 00:02:38.901
Lots of major companies

00:02:38.901 --> 00:02:41.334
already have their products
on Google Base.

00:02:41.334 --> 00:02:44.267
So when it's time
to make an ad for them,

00:02:44.267 --> 00:02:45.701
we need to understand

00:02:45.701 --> 00:02:48.534
how to get their items
from Google Base.

00:02:48.534 --> 00:02:51.367
Plenty of clients
still have their own APIs,

00:02:51.367 --> 00:02:55.801
but Base is
an important one to know.

00:02:55.801 --> 00:02:57.801
In my case,

00:02:57.801 --> 00:03:01.434
Google Gadgets
are the most certain way

00:03:01.434 --> 00:03:03.734
to generate traffic.

00:03:03.734 --> 00:03:07.734
Last year--Or last March,
just from Google Gadgets,

00:03:07.734 --> 00:03:11.634
it generated a million visitors
on my Websites,

00:03:11.634 --> 00:03:15.033
over 19 million page views,
and it was all free traffic.

00:03:15.033 --> 00:03:17.033
Didn't have to pay
for any of it.

00:03:17.033 --> 00:03:20.200
Gadgets are also used as ads,

00:03:20.200 --> 00:03:23.367
and we'll look at some examples
of those later.

00:03:23.367 --> 00:03:25.868
Google Maps just keeps getting
better and better.

00:03:25.868 --> 00:03:27.400
After seeing that keynote

00:03:27.400 --> 00:03:29.601
and seeing
the Rasmussens in action,

00:03:29.601 --> 00:03:33.734
I understand why
that's such a good API.

00:03:33.734 --> 00:03:36.801
For me,
Google Spreadsheets

00:03:36.801 --> 00:03:39.100
have become, like,
the Swiss Army Knife

00:03:39.100 --> 00:03:40.901
of applications,

00:03:40.901 --> 00:03:43.200
especially when we need,
like, a quick solution,

00:03:43.200 --> 00:03:46.200
you know,
some small data set.

00:03:46.200 --> 00:03:47.667
Just about every client
has somebody

00:03:47.667 --> 00:03:50.901
that knows
how to use a spreadsheet.

00:03:50.901 --> 00:03:54.200
Jerome will go
into a lot more details

00:03:54.200 --> 00:03:57.400
about AdSense
and the affiliates.

00:03:57.400 --> 00:04:00.067
YouTube has some
really neat API tricks.

00:04:00.067 --> 00:04:02.901
Picasa, of course,
is great for handling images.

00:04:02.901 --> 00:04:05.667
And Google Friend Connect,
it's about a year old.

00:04:05.667 --> 00:04:09.133
Has anybody ever heard
or used Google Friend Connect?

00:04:09.133 --> 00:04:11.067
I still run into people
who have never heard of it.

00:04:11.067 --> 00:04:14.601
But basically,

00:04:14.601 --> 00:04:17.234
it lets people
join your site,

00:04:17.234 --> 00:04:19.534
and then
you can do persistence,

00:04:19.534 --> 00:04:22.000
you know,
let them rate things,

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:23.667
have polls,

00:04:23.667 --> 00:04:26.167
and it's very easy
to set up and do.

00:04:26.167 --> 00:04:30.167
And they can log in
from other social services

00:04:30.167 --> 00:04:32.767
other than just Google's.

00:04:36.701 --> 00:04:40.367
We've broken monetization down
for our talk today

00:04:40.367 --> 00:04:41.968
into two sections--

00:04:41.968 --> 00:04:45.734
indirect and direct.

00:04:45.734 --> 00:04:48.234
By direct,
we mean people paying us

00:04:48.234 --> 00:04:49.667
to do certain things for them.

00:04:49.667 --> 00:04:50.801
By indirect,

00:04:50.801 --> 00:04:53.067
we mean the AdSense
and affiliate programs.

00:04:53.067 --> 00:04:54.868
We won't be mentioning
some of the others,

00:04:54.868 --> 00:04:56.334
since this is
a Google presentation,

00:04:56.334 --> 00:04:59.000
like Amazon.

00:05:00.834 --> 00:05:02.734
When working
directly for clients,

00:05:02.734 --> 00:05:07.367
it's common to quote
an hourly rate,

00:05:07.367 --> 00:05:10.234
and that's--

00:05:10.234 --> 00:05:12.434
For us, that's a little bit
less attractive,

00:05:12.434 --> 00:05:14.300
because it puts us
in competition

00:05:14.300 --> 00:05:17.267
with every other programmer
in the world directly,

00:05:17.267 --> 00:05:22.234
especially with
the low-cost labor markets.

00:05:22.234 --> 00:05:25.834
When we started making
Gadget ads for Google,

00:05:25.834 --> 00:05:27.868
they did want to pay us
by the hour,

00:05:27.868 --> 00:05:29.567
and it made perfect sense,

00:05:29.567 --> 00:05:31.567
because no one really knew

00:05:31.567 --> 00:05:33.901
how long it would take
to do this.

00:05:33.901 --> 00:05:36.901
We were doing things--
putting things together

00:05:36.901 --> 00:05:40.567
that hadn't been done
quite that way before,

00:05:40.567 --> 00:05:42.400
and one of the first
things I learned

00:05:42.400 --> 00:05:44.968
is there's a huge difference
between making a gadget for fun

00:05:44.968 --> 00:05:47.133
and making an ad.

00:05:47.133 --> 00:05:52.801
An ad, the appearance
is absolutely fixed.

00:05:52.801 --> 00:05:55.601
The tolerance
is plus or minus zero pixels.

00:05:55.601 --> 00:05:57.567
You have to nail it exactly.

00:05:57.567 --> 00:06:01.467
The first project I worked on
was a great one to learn from,

00:06:01.467 --> 00:06:03.701
because it had
some classic challenges.

00:06:03.701 --> 00:06:05.667
I think I was
the third developer.

00:06:05.667 --> 00:06:08.467
I don't know what happened
to the first one.

00:06:08.467 --> 00:06:10.634
The second one
said he was on vacation.

00:06:10.634 --> 00:06:14.300
And the day I started,
we were over budget

00:06:14.300 --> 00:06:17.701
and, like,
four weeks behind.

00:06:17.701 --> 00:06:21.067
And the client
was communication challenged.

00:06:21.067 --> 00:06:23.934
They would burn a whole week
between questions.

00:06:23.934 --> 00:06:26.868
And when the answer
finally arrived,

00:06:26.868 --> 00:06:29.634
it might be one sentence
in all caps--

00:06:29.634 --> 00:06:34.100
"JUST MATCH THE MOCK-UP."

00:06:34.100 --> 00:06:36.334
I also--When we started,

00:06:36.334 --> 00:06:38.567
I tried to let
the Google folks know

00:06:38.567 --> 00:06:40.434
I wasn't sure if I was
really professional enough

00:06:40.434 --> 00:06:42.801
to deal with their clients
directly.

00:06:42.801 --> 00:06:46.901
I'd had about, at that point,
about 25 years experience

00:06:46.901 --> 00:06:49.801
dealing with
the table-pounders in Detroit,

00:06:49.801 --> 00:06:51.501
but I'd never worked
with anybody

00:06:51.501 --> 00:06:53.400
in the advertising
industry before,

00:06:53.400 --> 00:06:56.033
and I imagined it would be
a lot different.

00:06:56.033 --> 00:06:58.200
It turns out clients really--

00:06:58.200 --> 00:07:00.234
or customers really
aren't that different

00:07:00.234 --> 00:07:01.467
in the different industries.

00:07:01.467 --> 00:07:03.934
And in advertising,
there's a lot--

00:07:03.934 --> 00:07:06.501
there's less table pounding.

00:07:06.501 --> 00:07:09.501
One point
about fixed-price bids

00:07:09.501 --> 00:07:12.567
is they make it easier
for people to buy from you.

00:07:12.567 --> 00:07:13.968
You always have to imagine

00:07:13.968 --> 00:07:16.667
what it's like for your contact
to go get approval

00:07:16.667 --> 00:07:18.534
to pay you to do something.

00:07:18.534 --> 00:07:21.868
So if you're talking
in terms of an hourly rate,

00:07:21.868 --> 00:07:24.901
it's almost like asking
for a blank check,

00:07:24.901 --> 00:07:26.701
because, you know,
really don't know how long

00:07:26.701 --> 00:07:28.234
it's gonna take,
and you can just say,

00:07:28.234 --> 00:07:30.000
"Well, not
to exceed this much,"

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:31.501
or something like that.

00:07:31.501 --> 00:07:34.767
But a fixed-price bid
makes it a lot easier for them

00:07:34.767 --> 00:07:38.701
to go to their vice president

00:07:38.701 --> 00:07:40.901
or whoever has to approve it
and say,

00:07:40.901 --> 00:07:42.868
"Okay, we need X dollars
to do this project."

00:07:42.868 --> 00:07:45.167
And then they can decide,
"Is it really worth it?"

00:07:45.167 --> 00:07:47.767
You know, "Do we want to spend
that money on it?"

00:07:54.367 --> 00:07:56.167
Okay, in our case,

00:07:56.167 --> 00:07:58.467
connecting the markets is,
to me,

00:07:58.467 --> 00:08:02.234
is the hardest part
of having your own business.

00:08:02.234 --> 00:08:06.801
For us, we were really lucky.

00:08:06.801 --> 00:08:08.234
Google reached out to us.

00:08:08.234 --> 00:08:11.634
We had demonstrated
some proficiency with the APIs.

00:08:11.634 --> 00:08:15.167
When the Gadget API was new,

00:08:15.167 --> 00:08:18.334
actually, I started making
some gadgets,

00:08:18.334 --> 00:08:20.133
kind of little games
and fun things,

00:08:20.133 --> 00:08:21.133
to impress my daughters.

00:08:21.133 --> 00:08:23.234
I might spend, like, a month

00:08:23.234 --> 00:08:25.067
working on something,
getting it ready,

00:08:25.067 --> 00:08:29.667
and they would be impressed
for about two minutes.

00:08:29.667 --> 00:08:33.033
But after a while, you know,
it became challenging.

00:08:33.033 --> 00:08:34.133
A lot of times I'd do things,

00:08:34.133 --> 00:08:37.200
you know, "Can I do this?
Can we do that?"

00:08:37.200 --> 00:08:41.200
And I started turning out
one or two gadgets a week.

00:08:41.200 --> 00:08:46.567
And so when
they decided to, uh...

00:08:46.567 --> 00:08:48.467
try to use Gadgets for ads,

00:08:48.467 --> 00:08:52.100
they reached out to about
8 or 12 of us in that category

00:08:52.100 --> 00:08:54.133
to find out
if we wanted to do it,

00:08:54.133 --> 00:08:57.000
you know, for money,
to do it professionally.

00:08:59.601 --> 00:09:02.400
I think one thing
I'd like to share,

00:09:02.400 --> 00:09:03.601
you know,
throughout my life,

00:09:03.601 --> 00:09:05.033
I've told people that...

00:09:05.033 --> 00:09:08.467
Find what you love to do,
and do it with all your might.

00:09:08.467 --> 00:09:11.033
And success
will follow from that.

00:09:11.033 --> 00:09:13.667
And I think it's true.
It's true in our case.

00:09:13.667 --> 00:09:15.801
I've also--I've--

00:09:15.801 --> 00:09:17.567
Talk about building alliances,

00:09:17.567 --> 00:09:19.534
I've been
in a lot of situations

00:09:19.534 --> 00:09:21.734
where the customer/vendor
relationship

00:09:21.734 --> 00:09:23.834
is adversarial.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:27.501
Like it's a fight
all the time.

00:09:27.501 --> 00:09:30.434
There's arguments,
dishonesty, and so forth.

00:09:30.434 --> 00:09:33.901
What I found works better
is to try to make an alliance.

00:09:33.901 --> 00:09:37.033
Try to find ways where everybody
comes out a winner,

00:09:37.033 --> 00:09:41.133
and that they're really glad
they did business with you.

00:09:41.133 --> 00:09:43.167
We have to keep
asking ourselves,

00:09:43.167 --> 00:09:46.367
"Given the level
of service we're providing,

00:09:46.367 --> 00:09:48.234
"would this customer

00:09:48.234 --> 00:09:51.100
decide to do business
with us again?"

00:09:51.100 --> 00:09:54.234
The early Gadget ad projects
were really hard for us,

00:09:54.234 --> 00:09:56.067
because we
were putting things together

00:09:56.067 --> 00:09:58.267
in ways
that hadn't been done before.

00:09:58.267 --> 00:10:00.968
Clients would get anxious.

00:10:00.968 --> 00:10:03.267
It would take three or four
tries to get something right.

00:10:03.267 --> 00:10:06.834
I make so many mistakes.

00:10:06.834 --> 00:10:08.667
One time it was late at night,

00:10:08.667 --> 00:10:10.701
and we were working
on something.

00:10:10.701 --> 00:10:13.734
We found out--you know,
we found out what to do,

00:10:13.734 --> 00:10:16.634
and it meant
redoing a lot of code.

00:10:16.634 --> 00:10:18.767
I mean, a lot,
and it was gonna take hours.

00:10:18.767 --> 00:10:22.000
And I was chatting
with the contact at Google,

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:24.567
and I said,
"Okay, I'll start on it now,

00:10:24.567 --> 00:10:26.100
and it'll be ready
in the morning."

00:10:26.100 --> 00:10:27.267
And he chatted back.

00:10:27.267 --> 00:10:29.467
He said,
"You're crazy, aren't you?"

00:10:29.467 --> 00:10:31.501
And of course he was right,

00:10:31.501 --> 00:10:33.567
but I think he meant it
in a good way.

00:10:33.567 --> 00:10:36.400
But that's an example

00:10:36.400 --> 00:10:37.901
of providing service

00:10:37.901 --> 00:10:43.000
above and beyond what
their expectations might be.

00:10:50.834 --> 00:10:53.033
Once you've connected
with the market

00:10:53.033 --> 00:10:56.400
and you start doing
contract work,

00:10:56.400 --> 00:10:58.334
an important point

00:10:58.334 --> 00:11:02.934
is to manage
client expectations.

00:11:02.934 --> 00:11:07.067
I learned that by watching
other people doing that.

00:11:07.067 --> 00:11:08.734
I noticed they were doing that.

00:11:08.734 --> 00:11:10.200
And I think
the important point there

00:11:10.200 --> 00:11:11.667
is you don't want
to set the clients up

00:11:11.667 --> 00:11:13.834
to be disappointed.

00:11:15.400 --> 00:11:19.000
My natural tendency is to put
the very best spin on things,

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:22.534
and sometimes things
actually do work out

00:11:22.534 --> 00:11:25.133
exactly perfect,
but usually not.

00:11:25.133 --> 00:11:27.801
So it's better not

00:11:27.801 --> 00:11:30.334
to set them up
to be disappointed.

00:11:32.934 --> 00:11:34.868
More often--Oh.

00:11:36.901 --> 00:11:38.033
More often than not,

00:11:38.033 --> 00:11:40.567
the people who decide
to place contracts

00:11:40.567 --> 00:11:42.267
aren't engineers themselves.

00:11:42.267 --> 00:11:45.300
They're probably experts
at something else,

00:11:45.300 --> 00:11:49.901
so you have to find out
how to communicate with them

00:11:49.901 --> 00:11:51.901
at their comfort level.

00:11:51.901 --> 00:11:54.000
One time
I was talking to a client,

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:55.868
and I said something
about the URL,

00:11:55.868 --> 00:11:58.734
and he said, "Oh, whoa,
don't get all technical on me."

00:11:58.734 --> 00:12:01.400
So you have to find out
where they're at

00:12:01.400 --> 00:12:03.200
and work there.

00:12:03.200 --> 00:12:06.067
I've seen sales guys
shoot themselves in the foot

00:12:06.067 --> 00:12:08.567
by trying to wow the CEO

00:12:08.567 --> 00:12:13.400
with the latest technical terms
and a lot of acronyms.

00:12:13.400 --> 00:12:14.901
You know, he or she,

00:12:14.901 --> 00:12:16.734
they're not gonna know
what that means.

00:12:16.734 --> 00:12:18.167
And it just doesn't--

00:12:18.167 --> 00:12:20.834
Bluffing just doesn't work
very well.

00:12:23.734 --> 00:12:25.467
Estimating costs,

00:12:25.467 --> 00:12:29.000
the only way I know to learn
to do it is to practice.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:31.701
There's kind of
a laundry list there

00:12:31.701 --> 00:12:34.734
of different things
you might think of

00:12:34.734 --> 00:12:36.200
to take into account,

00:12:36.200 --> 00:12:38.367
but the important part
is to practice.

00:12:38.367 --> 00:12:39.567
I practiced estimating

00:12:39.567 --> 00:12:41.234
how long is it gonna take me
to do this

00:12:41.234 --> 00:12:42.567
even when it doesn't matter,

00:12:42.567 --> 00:12:45.133
even if it's a project
I'm doing just for fun.

00:12:45.133 --> 00:12:47.467
And what I found is,

00:12:47.467 --> 00:12:49.100
for me,

00:12:49.100 --> 00:12:52.567
about 25% of the total time
of a project,

00:12:52.567 --> 00:12:57.000
about 25% I spent getting
to a working first draft,

00:12:57.000 --> 00:12:59.734
and then about 50%
of the time

00:12:59.734 --> 00:13:01.767
is for debugging

00:13:01.767 --> 00:13:04.734
and meeting
all the requirements.

00:13:04.734 --> 00:13:07.400
Sorry.

00:13:07.400 --> 00:13:10.367
And the remaining 25%
is testing.

00:13:10.367 --> 00:13:14.534
And of course, support goes on
till the last user is dead.

00:13:14.534 --> 00:13:18.300
So the best way to learn
to estimate well is to practice.

00:13:18.300 --> 00:13:19.901
Last year, one example,

00:13:19.901 --> 00:13:22.167
I missed an estimate
literally by half.

00:13:22.167 --> 00:13:26.067
And there were
some communication issues.

00:13:26.067 --> 00:13:28.567
There were some open-ended areas
in the requirements,

00:13:28.567 --> 00:13:30.234
and the client
interpreted them

00:13:30.234 --> 00:13:32.167
completely differently
than I did.

00:13:32.167 --> 00:13:35.367
So, you know, half pay
is better than no pay.

00:13:35.367 --> 00:13:36.834
At least I got paid for it,

00:13:36.834 --> 00:13:38.434
but the lesson learned

00:13:38.434 --> 00:13:40.334
was to really nail down
the requirements

00:13:40.334 --> 00:13:43.968
as well as I can.

00:13:43.968 --> 00:13:45.267
Scheduling.

00:13:45.267 --> 00:13:46.801
In our case,

00:13:46.801 --> 00:13:49.834
most of the projects
are due yesterday.

00:13:49.834 --> 00:13:51.901
So really all you can do

00:13:51.901 --> 00:13:55.100
is level the work
as best you can.

00:14:01.133 --> 00:14:02.934
Selling.

00:14:02.934 --> 00:14:04.367
You know,
people will give you--

00:14:04.367 --> 00:14:07.334
There's all kind of seminars
and books about selling.

00:14:07.334 --> 00:14:09.767
They'll give you all kinds
of advice about it.

00:14:09.767 --> 00:14:11.801
So don't take my word for it.

00:14:11.801 --> 00:14:14.033
Shop around.
See what really works for you.

00:14:14.033 --> 00:14:16.400
But this is what's always
worked for me.

00:14:16.400 --> 00:14:18.334
For me,
the most important thing

00:14:18.334 --> 00:14:21.734
is to be absolutely,
totally honest with clients.

00:14:21.734 --> 00:14:25.234
I've been in situations
where my boss, you know,

00:14:25.234 --> 00:14:28.033
at times in my job
would really want me to lie.

00:14:28.033 --> 00:14:29.567
They'd say,
"Okay, the lie is...

00:14:29.567 --> 00:14:31.067
This is what
we're gonna tell them."

00:14:31.067 --> 00:14:32.667
And I would never
go along with that.

00:14:32.667 --> 00:14:35.000
I've actually been fired
for not going along with that.

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:38.467
But I think people are glad
to do business with me

00:14:38.467 --> 00:14:40.234
once they learn that about me,

00:14:40.234 --> 00:14:44.601
that I'm not
gonna fake them out.

00:14:44.601 --> 00:14:46.667
Communicating clearly
is important.

00:14:46.667 --> 00:14:49.000
I wish I were doing better
at it right now,

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:50.934
but, uh...

00:14:50.934 --> 00:14:52.934
I think we've covered
that point.

00:14:52.934 --> 00:14:54.868
I can give you, uh...

00:14:57.734 --> 00:15:00.200
One important point
I want to make

00:15:00.200 --> 00:15:03.501
from this slide...

00:15:03.501 --> 00:15:04.701
And we heard it this morning.

00:15:04.701 --> 00:15:06.400
You know, they were talking
about that Wave,

00:15:06.400 --> 00:15:08.133
really cool stuff.

00:15:08.133 --> 00:15:10.601
And we get to see it today

00:15:10.601 --> 00:15:13.400
before it's, like,
even in an alpha release.

00:15:13.400 --> 00:15:16.434
So, in my mind,
what I'm thinking is,

00:15:16.434 --> 00:15:17.634
"Oh, this is great.

00:15:17.634 --> 00:15:20.334
"I can be ready
when our customers arrive.

00:15:20.334 --> 00:15:21.767
"I'll--I'll be prepared.

00:15:21.767 --> 00:15:24.367
"I'll understand how to do it,
how to work with it."

00:15:24.367 --> 00:15:25.868
So the point is,

00:15:25.868 --> 00:15:29.400
figure out what
your customers need next year

00:15:29.400 --> 00:15:32.868
and start
preparing for that now.

00:15:37.901 --> 00:15:40.234
The point about learning
what the market will bear

00:15:40.234 --> 00:15:42.300
and bid at or just below that--

00:15:42.300 --> 00:15:43.601
just a quick point--

00:15:43.601 --> 00:15:45.667
I don't want to be
the lowest bidder,

00:15:45.667 --> 00:15:47.067
unless it's
a government project.

00:15:47.067 --> 00:15:51.334
I'd rather be
the preferred bidder.

00:15:58.734 --> 00:16:00.667
Which projects to tackle?

00:16:00.667 --> 00:16:03.734
As work starts to, uh...

00:16:03.734 --> 00:16:06.601
As you start to get more
opportunities to bid on work,

00:16:06.601 --> 00:16:09.901
you have to decide what
you really want to go after

00:16:09.901 --> 00:16:11.667
and what you don't.

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:16.367
So kind of the questions
we would go through--

00:16:16.367 --> 00:16:19.067
"Is this project
in our niche?"

00:16:19.067 --> 00:16:21.334
Meaning, we're gonna give it--
if it is,

00:16:21.334 --> 00:16:23.400
we're gonna give it
the most aggressive price

00:16:23.400 --> 00:16:25.100
and the shortest lead time.

00:16:25.100 --> 00:16:26.868
It's something--
You know, we know how to do it,

00:16:26.868 --> 00:16:30.167
and we can do it as well
or better than anybody else.

00:16:30.167 --> 00:16:32.701
If the project
is close to what we--

00:16:32.701 --> 00:16:34.801
close to our niche,
in the neighborhood,

00:16:34.801 --> 00:16:36.434
then it's similar.

00:16:36.434 --> 00:16:39.367
You know, we'll try to come in
with a really good price

00:16:39.367 --> 00:16:41.234
and a decent lead time.

00:16:41.234 --> 00:16:43.934
If it's something we'd
really like to start doing,

00:16:43.934 --> 00:16:46.167
you could consider
buying the business,

00:16:46.167 --> 00:16:47.868
you know,
almost give it away,

00:16:47.868 --> 00:16:50.767
just to get the experience
at doing it.

00:16:50.767 --> 00:16:53.300
And some projects,

00:16:53.300 --> 00:16:55.300
if you see there's something
frightening about it,

00:16:55.300 --> 00:16:57.801
sometimes it's hard
to tell the client,

00:16:57.801 --> 00:16:59.567
"No, I don't want
to bid on that."

00:16:59.567 --> 00:17:02.300
It depends on your
relationship with them,

00:17:02.300 --> 00:17:04.334
but you may not be
in a position

00:17:04.334 --> 00:17:06.234
where it's comfortable
to say no,

00:17:06.234 --> 00:17:09.367
so what we've done at times is

00:17:09.367 --> 00:17:11.133
maybe say, "Okay, yes,

00:17:11.133 --> 00:17:13.868
but we'll bid just
on this part of the project."

00:17:13.868 --> 00:17:16.267
Or, "Yes, but here's
our price."

00:17:16.267 --> 00:17:19.300
And the price is set such that
if we do get it, okay.

00:17:19.300 --> 00:17:21.767
We won't mind too much.

00:17:24.801 --> 00:17:25.801
I don't know.

00:17:25.801 --> 00:17:27.234
You know,
everybody here, I guess,

00:17:27.234 --> 00:17:29.367
you know, you have a job,
you're working for somebody,

00:17:29.367 --> 00:17:31.634
or maybe you're working
for yourself.

00:17:31.634 --> 00:17:35.434
Somebody we'll call
an astute observer of patterns

00:17:35.434 --> 00:17:39.534
pointed this set of transitions
out to me.

00:17:39.534 --> 00:17:41.033
You know, starting off,

00:17:41.033 --> 00:17:43.033
you're, like, somebody
that's just a programmer,

00:17:43.033 --> 00:17:46.167
doing things because
they're interesting or fun.

00:17:46.167 --> 00:17:48.100
At that stage,

00:17:48.100 --> 00:17:50.667
you don't want to worry so much
about the monetization angle.

00:17:50.667 --> 00:17:53.400
You know, you make money
accidentally,

00:17:53.400 --> 00:17:55.868
or if you have to somehow,

00:17:55.868 --> 00:17:58.067
you know, through AdSense
or whatever.

00:17:58.067 --> 00:18:00.167
Then, as a developer,

00:18:00.167 --> 00:18:02.801
you start to do things

00:18:02.801 --> 00:18:05.434
where some problem
you have solved,

00:18:05.434 --> 00:18:07.734
because it was interesting,

00:18:07.734 --> 00:18:11.734
that solution you provided
will help somebody else,

00:18:11.734 --> 00:18:13.901
and they'll be willing to pay
for that solution.

00:18:13.901 --> 00:18:15.734
So in those,

00:18:15.734 --> 00:18:19.234
you can start picking up
some momentum that way.

00:18:19.234 --> 00:18:22.067
Then once you've done that
for a while,

00:18:22.067 --> 00:18:25.234
you feel like, "Okay,
this is getting more serious."

00:18:25.234 --> 00:18:28.400
And it becomes very important

00:18:28.400 --> 00:18:31.367
to cultivate repeat business
at that point.

00:18:31.367 --> 00:18:33.901
I want to tell one story.

00:18:33.901 --> 00:18:35.801
I was working with a client,

00:18:35.801 --> 00:18:39.234
and they fielded, like,
five different Gadget ads,

00:18:39.234 --> 00:18:42.868
you know, kind of all across
the map possibilities.

00:18:42.868 --> 00:18:45.067
And they ran those
for about a month,

00:18:45.067 --> 00:18:48.400
and then they picked
one winner of the five

00:18:48.400 --> 00:18:50.901
and said, "Okay,
we're gonna go with this one."

00:18:50.901 --> 00:18:53.968
And then they ran it
for about a month,

00:18:53.968 --> 00:18:55.767
and they decided
they wanted to make a change.

00:18:55.767 --> 00:18:57.734
The way their ads
were structured,

00:18:57.734 --> 00:19:00.634
there was four different topics

00:19:00.634 --> 00:19:04.567
and, uh...

00:19:04.567 --> 00:19:05.901
eight different sizes,

00:19:05.901 --> 00:19:07.601
so the change they needed

00:19:07.601 --> 00:19:09.767
was gonna hit
32 different places.

00:19:09.767 --> 00:19:11.601
So they wrote an email,
you know,

00:19:11.601 --> 00:19:13.133
"How long is this gonna take?

00:19:13.133 --> 00:19:15.934
How much is it gonna cost?
Is it difficult?"

00:19:15.934 --> 00:19:18.934
And the actual change
they needed

00:19:18.934 --> 00:19:21.567
was one of those
one-line-of-code-type changes.

00:19:21.567 --> 00:19:25.901
And I responded, I said,

00:19:25.901 --> 00:19:28.234
"It's done. No charge."

00:19:28.234 --> 00:19:29.534
You know,
it took about a minute.

00:19:29.534 --> 00:19:31.467
And I already had
a program in place

00:19:31.467 --> 00:19:33.167
to handle the repetitive stuff.

00:19:33.167 --> 00:19:36.267
And I think they were shocked
that that was the answer.

00:19:36.267 --> 00:19:38.267
"It's done,
and there's no charge?"

00:19:38.267 --> 00:19:42.467
And what they learned
about us at that point

00:19:42.467 --> 00:19:45.267
was--is that we weren't
gonna take advantage of them

00:19:45.267 --> 00:19:46.534
on some little something.

00:19:46.534 --> 00:19:49.334
They believe us when we say--
And so now when we say,

00:19:49.334 --> 00:19:51.734
"That change is gonna cost
several thousand dollars,"

00:19:51.734 --> 00:19:53.167
they believe it,

00:19:53.167 --> 00:19:54.968
'cause they know we're
gonna tell them the truth

00:19:54.968 --> 00:19:58.067
about the ones
that are really trivial.

00:20:02.400 --> 00:20:06.234
And they've become
our second-biggest customer.

00:20:06.234 --> 00:20:09.868
And actually,
I think if anybody else--

00:20:09.868 --> 00:20:12.400
IBM or whoever, you know--
went to them and said,

00:20:12.400 --> 00:20:14.501
"Okay, we can do
what Echo3 is doing,"

00:20:14.501 --> 00:20:17.334
it'd be a really
hard sell for them.

00:20:17.334 --> 00:20:20.968
You know, we've really
developed some loyalty.

00:20:24.367 --> 00:20:26.400
This is kind of a short list

00:20:26.400 --> 00:20:30.133
of some lessons learned.

00:20:30.133 --> 00:20:31.801
The example I just gave,

00:20:31.801 --> 00:20:34.334
using software
to automate repetitive tasks,

00:20:34.334 --> 00:20:35.901
you can see
where that helped.

00:20:35.901 --> 00:20:38.067
And we told the story
about looking out

00:20:38.067 --> 00:20:41.033
for open-ended statements
and requirements.

00:20:41.033 --> 00:20:43.200
One way I shoot myself
in the foot,

00:20:43.200 --> 00:20:46.200
I try to turn things around
really quickly.

00:20:52.100 --> 00:20:55.501
Recently, I published
a really big bug

00:20:55.501 --> 00:20:57.501
in kind of
a high-profile project,

00:20:57.501 --> 00:20:58.634
and you know what?

00:20:58.634 --> 00:21:00.300
It tested, it looked okay
and everything,

00:21:00.300 --> 00:21:03.501
but I realized I was looking
at some cached results.

00:21:03.501 --> 00:21:05.901
And so, anyway,

00:21:05.901 --> 00:21:08.734
there's no such thing
as too much testing.

00:21:08.734 --> 00:21:11.501
Sometimes with clients,
you know,

00:21:11.501 --> 00:21:15.601
they'll want to,
say, do a new ad,

00:21:15.601 --> 00:21:17.601
and they want
to talk about it on the phone,

00:21:17.601 --> 00:21:18.767
and while you're talking--

00:21:18.767 --> 00:21:20.667
you haven't even seen
a mock-up yet.

00:21:20.667 --> 00:21:22.234
"Can you give me
a quick estimate?

00:21:22.234 --> 00:21:24.200
You know, some kind
of ballpark thing?"

00:21:24.200 --> 00:21:25.734
So one thing I found is,

00:21:25.734 --> 00:21:28.167
if I think something's
gonna take me three days,

00:21:28.167 --> 00:21:29.834
I should say six days.

00:21:29.834 --> 00:21:32.267
And if they want to say,
"Well, worse case."

00:21:32.267 --> 00:21:35.467
So for me,
I multiply that by four.

00:21:35.467 --> 00:21:37.601
And the last part--

00:21:37.601 --> 00:21:41.667
they told me to use a picture.

00:21:41.667 --> 00:21:44.501
One thing I found, I think
I've blown some business

00:21:44.501 --> 00:21:45.968
by using rough drafts.

00:21:45.968 --> 00:21:48.234
I don't have any problem
with a rough draft.

00:21:48.234 --> 00:21:49.400
You know, "I get it.

00:21:49.400 --> 00:21:51.300
Okay, yeah, the images
will look better later."

00:21:51.300 --> 00:21:52.667
And,
"We're gonna have somebody

00:21:52.667 --> 00:21:54.834
that's really good with graphics
come back and do this."

00:21:54.834 --> 00:21:57.934
But one lesson learned
is use a wire frame.

00:21:57.934 --> 00:22:01.234
Some people just aren't--
they're not gonna play with you.

00:22:01.234 --> 00:22:02.801
They're not
gonna be that imaginative

00:22:02.801 --> 00:22:05.167
about how this might look.

00:22:05.167 --> 00:22:09.701
And the big warm-up
for Jerome coming up now,

00:22:09.701 --> 00:22:12.501
you'll be glad to hear.

